result.question:
Build a current (June 2026) content pack for 9 AI benchmarks for an AI-literacy education site aimed at university students from mixed, non-expert backgrounds. The benchmarks: SimpleQA, LongBench v2, BFCL (Berkeley Function Calling Leaderboard), OSWorld, OmniDocBench, MMMU-Pro, Design2Code, EQ-Bench (Creative Writing), Global-MMLU.

For EACH benchmark return, with a source URL for every factual claim and especially for every leader number:
(1) what it measures, in one plain sentence with no jargon-defined-by-jargon, ideally framed through a difficulty contrast;
(2) why it matters in the AI landscape and for a student trying to pick a model for a task;
(3) how scoring works: the metric and scale, who maintains the leaderboard, and the official leaderboard or paper URL plus the date it was last updated;
(4) watch out for: known criticisms, data contamination concerns, and saturation status (is it effectively solved?);
(5) the current (June 2026) top-3 leaders, each with the model and lab, the score COPIED VERBATIM as the board states it (keep intervals like "x +/- y" and any split-name caveats), an as-of date, a source URL, and whether each score is self-reported or independently evaluated, and whether it is disputed;
(6) whether the top ranks are a statistical tie (a near-tie), stated plainly;
(7) a one-line baseline anchor a non-expert needs to read the top score (random chance, expert human level, prior state of the art);
(8) if NO trustworthy current board exists (for example a JavaScript-only board that cannot be read, or one where every entry is self-reported), say so explicitly and give the single most-cited DATED anchor figure instead of guessing.

Adversarially verify every top-3 before returning it. Flag any benchmark where the top score is disputed, self-reported only, or moving fast. Style rule: zero em dashes or en dashes anywhere in the prose; use commas, colons, or hyphens instead.
